05911nam a22008175i 9780814786819DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20012001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147868197 a10.18574/nyu/9780814786819.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548169  a(OCoLC)779828373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM1068 .P37 2001 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a30600aPassing :bIdentity and Interpretation in Sexuality, Race, and Religion /ced. by Maria C. Sanchez, Linda Schlossberg. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexual Cultures ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Rites of Passing -- t1 Telling Tales: Brandon Teena, Billy Tipton, and Transgender Biography -- t2 Passing Like Me: Jewish Chameleonism and the Politics of Race -- t3 Whiteness Invisible: Early Mexican American Writing and the Color of Literary History -- t4 Passing Lines Immigration and the Performance of American Identity -- t5 From Victorian Parlor to Physique Pictorial: The Male Nude and Homosexual Identity -- t6 Slumming -- t7 The “Self-Made Man” Male Impersonation and the New Woman -- t8 Mimesis in the Face of Fear: Femme Queens, Butch Queens, and Gender Play in the Houses of Greater Newark -- t9 “The Church’s Closet” Confessionals, Victorian Catholicism, and the Crisis of Identification -- t10 Moses’ Wilderness Tabernacle -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPassing for what you are not--whether it is mulattos passing as white, Jews passing as Christian, or drag queens passing as women--can be a method of protection or self-defense. But it can also be a uniquely pleasurable experience, one that trades on the erotics of secrecy and revelation. It is precisely passing's radical playfulness, the way it asks us to reconsider our assumptions and forces our most cherished fantasies of identity to self-destruct, that is centrally addressed in Passing: Identity and Interpretation in Sexuality, Race, and Religion. Identity in Western culture is largely structured around visibility, whether in the service of science (Victorian physiognomy), psychoanalysis (Lacan's mirror stage), or philosophy (the Panopticon). As such, it is charged with anxieties regarding classification and social demarcation. Passing wreaks havoc with accepted systems of social recognition and cultural intelligibility, blurring the carefully-marked lines of race, gender, and class. Bringing together theories of passing across a host of disciplines--from critical race theory and lesbian and gay studies, to literary theory and religious studies--Passing complicates our current understanding of the visual and categories of identity. Contributors: Michael Bronski, Karen McCarthy Brown, Bradley Epps, Judith Halberstam, Peter Hitchcock, Daniel Itzkovitz, Patrick O'Malley, Miriam Peskowitz, María C. Sánchez Linda Schlossberg, and Sharon Ullman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPassing (Identity). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBronski, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Karen McCarthy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpps, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalberstam, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitchcock, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aItzkovitz, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Malley, Patrick R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeskowitz, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go